SIMPLE: practice
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Practice
<hw>Prac"tice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>praktike</ets>, <ets>practique</ets>, F. <ets>pratique</ets>,
formerly also, <ets>practique</ets>, LL. <ets>practica</ets>, fr. Gr.
<?/, fr. <?/ practical. See <er>Practical</er>, and cf.
<er>Pratique</er>, <er>Pretty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Frequently
repeated or customary action; habitual performance; a succession of acts
of a similar kind; usage; habit; custom; <as>as, the <ex>practice</ex>
of rising early; the <ex>practice</ex> of making regular entries of
accounts; the <ex>practice</ex> of daily exercise.</as></def> <-- also
commonly practise -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A heart . . . exercised with covetous <qex>practices</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Pet. ii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Customary or constant use; state of being
used.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Obsolete words may be revived when they are more sounding or more
significant than those in <qex>practice</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Skill or dexterity acquired by use;
expertness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧His nice fence and his active
<xex>practice</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Actual performance; application of knowledge; --
opposed to <xex>theory</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There are two functions of the soul, -- contemplation and
<qex>practice</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a distinction, but no opposition, between theory and
<qex>practice</qex>; each, to a certain extent, supposes the other;
theory is dependent on <qex>practice</qex>; <qex>practice</qex> must
have preceded theory.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Systematic exercise for instruction or discipline;
<as>as, the troops are called out for <ex>practice</ex>; she neglected
<ex>practice</ex> in music.</as></def> <-- practice makes perfect. MW10
2a. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Application of science to the wants of men; the
exercise of any profession; professional business; <as>as, the
<ex>practice</ex> of medicine or law; a large or lucrative
<ex>practice</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Practice</qex> is exercise of an art, or the application of a
science in life, which application is itself an art.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Skillful or artful management; dexterity in
contrivance or the use of means; art; stratagem; artifice; plot; --
usually in a bad sense.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sought to have that by <qex>practice</qex> which he could not
by prayer.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A easy and concise method of
applying the rules of arithmetic to questions which occur in trade and
business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The form, manner, and order of
conducting and carrying on suits and prosecutions through their various
stages, according to the principles of law and the rules laid down by
the courts.</def> <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Custom; usage; habit; manner.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Practice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Practice
<hw>Prac"tice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Practiced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Practicing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Often
written <ets>practise</ets>, <ets>practised</ets>,
<ets>practising</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To do or perform
frequently, customarily, or habitually; to make a practice of; <as>as,
to <ex>practice</ex> gaming</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Incline not my heart . .
. <xex>practice</xex> wicked works.⟦rdquo⟧ <-- also commonly practise
--> <rj><au>Ps. cxli. 4.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exercise, or follow, as a profession, trade, art,
etc., <as>as, to <ex>practice</ex> law or medicine</as>.</def><-- = MW10
1c. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exercise one's self in, for instruction or
improvement, or to acquire discipline or dexterity; <as>as, to
<ex>practice</ex> gunnery; to <ex>practice</ex> music.</as></def> <-- =
MW10 2a -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put into practice; to carry out; to act upon; to
commit; to execute; to do.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Aught but Talbot's shadow
whereon to <xex>practice</xex> your severity.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As this advice ye <qex>practice</qex> or neglect.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make use of; to employ.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In malice to this good knight's wife, I <qex>practiced</qex>
Ubaldo and Ricardo to corrupt her.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To teach or accustom by practice; to
train.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In church they are taught to love God; after church they are
<qex>practiced</qex> to love their neighbor.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Practice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Practice
<hw>Prac"tice</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Often written
<ets>practise</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perform certain acts
frequently or customarily, either for instruction, profit, or amusement;
<as>as, to <ex>practice</ex> with the broadsword or with the rifle; to
<ex>practice</ex> on the piano.</as></def> <-- also commonly
<asp>practise</asp> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To learn by practice; to form a habit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They shall <qex>practice</qex> how to live secure.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Practice</qex> first over yourself to reign.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To try artifices or stratagems.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will <qex>practice</qex> against thee by poison.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To apply theoretical science or knowledge, esp. by
way of experiment; to exercise or pursue an employment or profession,
esp. that of medicine or of law.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I am] little inclined to <qex>practice</qex> on others, and as
little that others should <qex>practice</qex> on me.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Practiced</ent>⟦br⟧
